				\begin{document}$${\sigma }_{pol}=P\,n$$\end{document}, where P is the polarization vector and n is the unit normal to the surface. When a ferroelectric surface contacts with a conductive layer (i.e., ITO), polarization charges at the ferroelectric surface will be screened by free charges in the conductive layer. The distribution of screening charges in the conductive layer, very near the interface with the ferroelectric, leads to several important thickness-dependent electrical phenomena in ferroelectrics. A depolarization field can be formed due to the slight offset between the polarization charges at the ferroelectric surface and the screening charges in the conductive layer24–26. Assume that the ferroelectric is homogeneously-poled, the interface states and space charge in the ferroelectric may be ignored25, so that the polarization charges are localized at the ferroelectric/conductive-layer interface. The depolarization field (Ed) in the ferroelectric can be represented as1Ed=−pεf(2εf/d2εf/d+εc/ls)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
